🍷CHEERS!🍷National Wine Day is coming up and I’ve been trying to figure out how to upgrade my wine storage. Welllll this @vintecclub 201 bottle multi-temp wine refrigerator from @nfmpics is the perfect answer! 

With the purchase of a vintec cellar not only do you get piece of mind knowing your bottles with be kept in great condition but you also get access to their members only club for wine tastings, cellaring tips, and a dedicated concierge to help grow your collection. It’s own app, OENO, helps you catalogue your wines for easy finding and gives valuable insight on drinking window, comparable bottles, and all the details on the wines you’ve collected so far. Nothing pairs better with a bottle of wine the a vintec fridge!

Pizza is very similar to BBQ. Just about everywhere I’ve been lucky enough to travel has their version or their take on a pizza. NY has it’s slice, Chicago has their deep dish, Japan has their saltier and smokier version of a Neapolitan pie, Sicily has their “sfincione”, and of course, the God Father of them all is that puffy, leopard spotted crust you only get from a wood burning oven in Napoli. I love everything about it.

I started watching Emeril Live on @foodnetwork when I was 10 years old and after the first time I heard him yell “BAM” as he served a plate of food to the hungry audience, I was hooked. That Christmas I asked for two things: a shot gun to duck hunt with and an @emeril set of pots and pans. I’ve always know I was going to be in this industry in some form or fashion always hoping to make the same connection with people, through food as Emeril did. 

I started washing dishes for @sam4chef @nickandsams when I was in high school. Progressed to prep work, salads, and learning to work the grill in a high volume environment. Played football @greenwavefb in New Orleans and worked in kitchen all over the city. Graduated, designed restaurant concepts but missed cooking so I left the US to travel, eat, learn, explore, and get lost. 

The more I learned the more I realized how little I actually knew about the world but one thing I did know was I wanted to cook at the highest level. I moved to New York to work at @elevenmadisonpark for @danielhumm @chefbrianlockwood COVID sent me home, where I opened helped @shugknight17 open his baby @shugsbagels and married my best friend @chandlercrumblish 

A few months later, I got the call started the process of getting cast for #ciaohouse. Three months later, I flew out to Italy to film an 8 episode long series for Food Network and my life came full circle being on the same network I grew up watching 20 years prior. 

These 8 episodes have put so much into perspective for me. It’s humbled me, brought me closer to people I love and work with, introduced me to people I’ll hold dear until I die, it’s been a blessing I never imagined would come true but it’s one I’ll never take for granted. I have too many people to mention and thank but know that every one of you reading this has played an incredibly important role in the getting me to where I’m at now in my life and in my career. As cliche as it is, dreams do come true if only you believe. Thanks for the wild ride!

Just an appreciation post for my best friend and biggest supporter @chandlercrumblish! I couldn’t be more proud of and grateful for everything this woman stands for. She’s beautiful, kind, funny, forgiving, smart, loyal, caring, passionate, dedicated, hard working, grounded, and real. Everything I do, I do to make her proud!

Confit artichoke, grilled chicken, preserved lemon and fresh ricotta lasagna made with basil pasta sheets. Make the pasta, blanch the sheets, assemble, cook, press over night while cooling, bring to room temp the next day, bake at high heat until edges are crispy and warmed through. Lasagna is surprisingly hard to do well but when it is, there’s not a whole lot I love more.

Check out this delicious grilled corn pasta recipe from friend of NFM @chefprestonpaine ! If you need your own fridge for chilling wine pairings, we know a place 👀

Ingredients:

2tbsp Oil

1tbsp Capers

¼c Charred Red Peppers, Chopped

½ Lemon Zest and Juice

1.5tbsp Shallot, Small Dice

1tbsp Garlic, Minced

2tbsp Sundried Tomatoes, Julienned

2ea Green Onions

2ea Ears of Corn, Charred and Cut Off Cob

3tbsp Unsalted Butter

1c White Wine

½c Grated Parmesan

1 Box of Rigatoni Pasta

1. Turn a burner on your gas stove on high heat, place a shucked ear of corn directly onto the burner to char
2. Rotate until all sides are charred on the outside
3. Once charred, set aside to cool
4. Once cool, cut the kernels off of the cob
5. Bring a salted pot of water to a boil
6. Add oil to a pan and turn to medium heat
7. Once hot, add and sweat the shallots until translucent, 2-3 minutes
8. Once translucent, add your garlic and cook until soft stirring constantly, 1-2 minutes
9. Deglaze with white wine and add the capers, red peppers, and corn and let the white wine reduce by half
10. Add unsalted butter, lemon zest, parmesan, and cooked and drained pasta then stir until combined
11. Season with salt, lemon juice, and pepper to taste
12. Garnish with green onions and enjoy!

Beet • Green Cardamom • Rose Vinegar
Red beets are spun on a Japanese vegetable sheeter and cut into ribbons (see second picture). They are then rolled into tight bundles looking like a fruit roll up, tied, vacuum sealed with toasted cardamom, yuzu oil, and woody herbs. Once they’re cooked and cooled, they are topped with sweetened whipped labneh scented with tarragon oil and fried garlic. Served with the reduced cooking liquid.
